  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Reviewing Tailwind Configuration**\n\nI\'m now diving into the specifics of configuring `src/index.css`. I\'m starting by reviewing how theme definitions are handled in Tailwind CSS v4. I\'m focusing on the `@theme` directive, which replaces the `tailwind.config.js` file used in prior versions of Tailwind CSS, as indicated in the prompt.\n\n\n**Importing Tailwind CSS**\n\nI\'ve confirmed that the only way to import Tailwind CSS is via the global CSS file using `@import \"tailwindcss\";\". Configuring it as a PostCSS plugin is not necessary unless absolutely required, though I am making note of the possibility to declare custom theme values within the `@theme` directive, directly within `src/index.css`. I\'ve added some examples, like custom font families and animation definitions.\n\n\n**Implementing CSS Variables**\n\nI\'m now integrating CSS variables for light and dark mode support directly into the CSS. I\'m defining a set of variables for colors and surface levels within `:root`, which I\'ll then use to style the application. The `.dark` class overrides these variables for dark mode. I\'m pleased with how this offers a clean approach.\n\n\n**Mapping CSS Variables**\n\nI\'m now focusing on directly mapping CSS variables to Tailwind CSS utility classes within the `@theme` block. I realize this approach leverages Tailwind v4\'s ability to handle CSS variables as theme values or fallbacks, enabling dynamic theming. I\'m exploring the potential for concise and adaptable styles. I can\'t wait to see this work in practice!\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will edit `/src/index.css` to import custom Google Fonts (`Inter`, `JetBrains Mono`, and `Space Grotesk`), support Tailind v4 variables mapping, and implement fluent dark/light modes."
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 6
      nanos: 869748830
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
